$rdtime:readTimeGet
The rapid advancement of technology over the last few decades has fundamentally altered the way we consume information. In the past, reading was often a quiet ritual that required deep concentration and silence. Today, however, we are constantly bombarded by a literal avalanche of short messages, social media notifications, and catchy headlines. This shift has given rise to what experts call "skimming culture," where the brain becomes accustomed to processing data in small fragments rather than engaging with long-form content.

Despite these changes, deep reading remains a vital skill for developing critical thinking. Research suggests that when a person immerses themselves in a complex narrative, their brain creates intricate visual images and establishes logical connections that are simply not triggered by scrolling through a digital feed. Reading trains our cognitive endurance, allowing us to maintain focus on a single task for longer periods.

Interestingly, reading speed is often influenced by oneâ€™s emotional state and environment. The average adult reads at a pace of about two hundred to three hundred words per minute. Testing this rate helps us understand how efficiently we absorb new material. Ultimately, speed should never come at the expense of comprehension. The true goal of any text is to leave an impression or spark a new idea.
